Note:
This file implements the "runa run" compile-and-run orchestration (task Q2b).

It sits directly on top of the Q2a subprocess primitives in process_manager
(process_run = fork + execve + wait, returning the child's decoded exit code)
and drives a complete source-to-running-program flow:

  1. Compile the input .runa source to assembly (.s) by invoking the genuine
     compiler pipeline entry points (read -> lex -> parse -> codegen), the same
     entry points the standalone compiler_driver "main" uses.
  2. Assemble the .s to an object (.o) by running /usr/bin/as.
  3. Link the .o against the Runa runtime object with /usr/bin/gcc (gcc supplies
     crt0/libc startup, matching the project's external build recipe).
  4. Execute the freshly built binary and surface its exit code to the caller.

Each external program is launched via process_run with an argv array marshalled
in the exact shape the Q2a contract requires: a heap block of 8-byte C-string
pointers terminated by a 0 entry, with argv[0] being the program name. Runa
strings are NUL-terminated byte buffers (this is how every path in the codebase
is already handed to the open/execve syscalls), so each argv entry is simply the
Runa string pointer itself -- no separate string-to-cstring conversion primitive
exists or is needed.

This file consists of the following functions/features/operation types:
- marshal_argv / free_argv: build and release NULL-terminated C pointer arrays
- empty_envp / free_envp: provide an empty environment vector
- compile_source_to_asm: reuse of the real compiler pipeline (read/lex/parse/gen)
- runa_run: the end-to-end compile, assemble, link, execute orchestration
:End Note

Note: process_run / process_execve / process_fork / process_wait (Q2a).
Import "runtime/integration/system_interface/wrappers/process_manager.runa" as ProcessManager

Note: Pointer-sized heap allocation and release for the argv/envp arrays.
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Layout

Note: Raw pointer and integer writes into the argv/envp arrays.
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/memory_core.runa" as Memory

Note: List length / element access for the caller-supplied argument list.
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/list.runa" as ListPrimitive

Note: String concatenation for temp-path construction and basename extraction.
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_primitive.runa" as StringPrimitive

Note: NUL-terminated string length scanning for basename extraction.
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa" as StringCore

Note: Best-effort temp-file removal (unlink) between and after pipeline stages.
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/io/file_io.runa" as FileIO

Note: ============================================================================
Note: CONSTANTS
Note: ============================================================================

Note: Absolute path of the Runa runtime object. This is the install-relative
Note: runtime artifact that gcc links against to satisfy the runtime's syscall
Note: wrappers, memory manager, and string primitives. It is isolated in a single
Note: accessor so that relocating the runtime object (for example after the
Note: bootstrap/ directory is renamed at v1.0) is a one-line change here. The
Note: value resolved on this host is the v0.0.8.4.5.3.5 runtime object, which is
Note: the runtime currently produced by the build pipeline.
Process called "runtime_object_path" returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    The runtime object location is an install detail, not a value baked into the
    orchestration logic, so it is exposed through a single accessor rather than
    scattered string literals. Returning the literal pointer is correct because
    Runa string literals are stable, NUL-terminated byte buffers for the lifetime
    of the program, exactly what gcc's argv needs.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Returns the absolute path of the runtime object that gcc links against. The
    path points at bootstrap/v0.0.8.4.5.3.5/runtime/runtime.o relative to the
    monorepo root; expressed absolutely so it is independent of the process CWD,
    which differs between compilation (bootstrap/v0.0.8.5) and execution.
    @End Implementation
    Return "/mnt/d/SybertneticsUmbrella/SybertneticsAISolutions/MonoRepo/RunaLang/runa/bootstrap/v0.0.8.4.5.3.5/runtime/runtime.o"
End Process

Note: Absolute path of the system assembler.
Process called "assembler_path" returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    process_execve needs an absolute executable path; it does not perform PATH
    resolution. The host's assembler lives at /usr/bin/as (verified present), so
    that absolute path is returned directly.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Returns the NUL-terminated literal "/usr/bin/as".
    @End Implementation
    Return "/usr/bin/as"
End Process

Note: Absolute path of the system C compiler / linker driver.
Process called "linker_path" returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    gcc is used as the link driver because it supplies crt0/libc startup objects
    that the produced program needs, matching the project's external build recipe
    ("gcc x.o runtime.o -o x -lm"). process_execve requires an absolute path, and
    the host's gcc is at /usr/bin/gcc (verified present).
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Returns the NUL-terminated literal "/usr/bin/gcc".
    @End Implementation
    Return "/usr/bin/gcc"
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: ARGV / ENVP MARSHALLING
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "marshal_argv" takes args_list as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    process_run / process_execve consume argv as a heap block of 8-byte C-string
    pointers terminated by a 0 entry. The caller assembles its arguments as a
    Runa List of string pointers (each a NUL-terminated byte buffer, which is
    precisely the C-string representation the kernel's execve expects -- the same
    representation every path in this codebase is already handed to open/execve).
    This Process converts that List into the contiguous, NULL-terminated pointer
    array execve requires. No string copying or conversion is performed: a Runa
    string pointer IS a valid C string, so each pointer is stored verbatim.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Steps:
      1. Read the element count from the List via list_length.
      2. Allocate (count + 1) pointer slots of 8 bytes each = (count + 1) * 8
         bytes on the owned heap, so the trailing slot can hold the 0 terminator.
      3. For each index i in 0..count-1, fetch the i-th element (a Runa string
         pointer) with list_get and store it at byte offset i*8 with
         memory_set_pointer.
      4. Write a 0 pointer at the final slot (offset count*8) to terminate the
         vector.
      5. Return the array base pointer. On allocation failure (allocate returns
         0) return 0 so callers can detect and abort.
    A NULL or empty List yields a single-slot array holding only the 0
    terminator, which is a valid (argument-less) argv -- though callers always
    supply at least argv[0].
    @End Implementation
    Let count be proc list_length from ListPrimitive with args_list
    Let slot_count be count plus 1
    Let total_bytes be slot_count multiplied by 8
    Let array be proc allocate from Layout with total_bytes
    If array is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let index be 0
    While index is less than count:
        Let element be proc list_get from ListPrimitive with args_list, index
        Let offset be index multiplied by 8
        proc memory_set_pointer from Memory with array, offset, element
        Set index to index plus 1
    End While
    Let terminator_offset be count multiplied by 8
    proc memory_set_pointer from Memory with array, terminator_offset, 0
    Return array
End Process

Process called "free_argv" takes argv as Integer returns Nothing:
    @Reasoning
    marshal_argv allocates one contiguous pointer array on the owned heap. The
    array stores BORROWED pointers (the caller's List elements and string
    literals), so only the array spine is freed here -- never the pointed-to
    strings, which the caller still owns.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Guards against a 0 pointer (allocation failure / already freed) and otherwise
    releases the array spine with deallocate.
    @End Implementation
    If argv is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If
    proc deallocate from Layout with argv
    Return
End Process

Process called "empty_envp" returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    The Q2a contract allows envp to point at a single 0 entry for an empty
    environment. "runa run" launches the build tools and the target program with
    a clean, empty environment so the run is reproducible and does not leak the
    parent shell's variables into the assembled program's view; as and gcc locate
    their own support files via absolute install paths and do not require
    inherited environment to function for this fixed recipe.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Allocates a single 8-byte slot and writes 0 into it, yielding a valid empty
    environment vector. Returns 0 on allocation failure.
    @End Implementation
    Let envp be proc allocate from Layout with 8
    If envp is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    proc memory_set_pointer from Memory with envp, 0, 0
    Return envp
End Process

Process called "free_envp" takes envp as Integer returns Nothing:
    @Reasoning
    Releases the single-slot environment vector allocated by empty_envp. Mirrors
    free_argv: only the spine is owned here.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Guards against 0 and frees with deallocate.
    @End Implementation
    If envp is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If
    proc deallocate from Layout with envp
    Return
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: TEMP PATH CONSTRUCTION
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "basename_of" takes path as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Temp artifacts are named after the input's basename so a user can correlate
    /tmp/<base>.s / .o / exe with the source they ran. The basename is the
    substring after the final '/'. No Date or random component is used (neither
    is available in this context), so repeated runs of the same source overwrite
    the prior run's temp files deterministically -- which is the intended,
    self-cleaning behaviour.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Scans the NUL-terminated path for the last '/' (byte value 47) and copies the
    bytes after it into a freshly allocated, NUL-terminated buffer. If the path
    contains no '/', the whole path is the basename and is duplicated. The
    returned buffer is owned by the caller and must be deallocated. Returns 0 on
    allocation failure.
    @End Implementation
    Let length be proc string_length from StringCore with path
    Let last_slash be 0 minus 1
    Let scan be 0
    While scan is less than length:
        Let byte_value be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with path, scan
        If byte_value is equal to 47:
            Set last_slash to scan
        End If
        Set scan to scan plus 1
    End While
    Let start be last_slash plus 1
    Let base_length be length minus start
    Let buffer be proc allocate from Layout with base_length plus 1
    If buffer is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let copy_index be 0
    While copy_index is less than base_length:
        Let source_offset be start plus copy_index
        Let copied_byte be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with path, source_offset
        proc memory_set_byte from Memory with buffer, copy_index, copied_byte
        Set copy_index to copy_index plus 1
    End While
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with buffer, base_length, 0
    Return buffer
End Process

Process called "build_temp_path" takes basename as Integer, suffix as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Produces an absolute temp path of the form /tmp/<basename><suffix>. Centralized
    so the .s, .o, and executable paths are built identically and the /tmp prefix
    lives in exactly one place.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Concatenates "/tmp/" + basename, then appends suffix, freeing the intermediate
    buffer so only the final NUL-terminated path is returned. The caller owns and
    must deallocate the result. Returns 0 if either concatenation fails to allocate.
    @End Implementation
    Let prefix_plus_base be proc string_concat from StringPrimitive with "/tmp/", basename
    If prefix_plus_base is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let full_path be proc string_concat from StringPrimitive with prefix_plus_base, suffix
    proc deallocate from Layout with prefix_plus_base
    Return full_path
End Process

Process called "best_effort_unlink" takes path as Integer returns Nothing:
    @Reasoning
    Temp files are removed as soon as they are no longer needed, but a failed
    unlink (file already gone, permissions) must never abort the run -- the run's
    success is defined solely by the stages succeeding, not by cleanup.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Guards against a 0 path and otherwise calls delete_file, ignoring its return
    value (delete_file is itself a no-op on a 0 path and returns 0/1 without
    raising).
    @End Implementation
    If path is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If
    Let unused be proc delete_file from FileIO with path
    Return
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: COMPILE STAGE (reuse of the real compiler pipeline)
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "compile_source_to_asm" takes input_path as Integer, output_s_path as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    "runa run" must compile real source, not accept a pre-built .s, so this stage
    reuses the genuine compiler pipeline entry points -- the SAME functions the
    standalone compiler_driver "main" invokes: runtime_read_file to load the
    source, lexer_create / parser_create / parser_parse_program to produce the
    AST, and compile_program to lower the AST through HIR/MIR/LIR/codegen and
    write the assembly. These are resolved as link-time externals exactly as they
    are in compiler_driver (they are not module-local symbols), so no source is
    duplicated. We deliberately do NOT call process_imports here: that symbol is
    defined only inside compiler_driver.runa alongside a rival "main", and pulling
    it in would force the rival main into the link. Single-file run targets (the
    common case for "runa run") need no import merge; multi-file builds go through
    the full driver. This is the (a)/(b) hybrid documented in the task: the real
    pipeline (a) is reused for read/lex/parse/codegen, while import merging is left
    to the full driver rather than re-linking it here.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Steps, each guarded:
      1. runtime_read_file(input_path) -> source. 0 means the file could not be
         opened; report and return 1.
      2. lexer_create(source) -> lexer.
      3. parser_create(lexer) -> parser.
      4. parser_parse_program(parser) -> program. 0 means a parse failure; report,
         release source, and return 1.
      5. compile_program(program, output_s_path). Nonzero means codegen failed;
         report and return 1.
    Returns 0 on success. The intermediate AST/lexer/parser allocations are owned
    by the pipeline and torn down by the produced program's own ownership; the
    source buffer is released on the parse-failure path where the pipeline has not
    yet taken ownership.
    @End Implementation
    Let source be runtime_read_file(input_path)
    If source is equal to 0:
        Alert "[runa run] compile: could not open input source file"
        Return 1
    End If
    Let lexer be lexer_create(source)
    Let parser be parser_create(lexer)
    Let program be parser_parse_program(parser)
    If program is equal to 0:
        Alert "[runa run] compile: parsing failed"
        deallocate(source)
        Return 1
    End If
    Let compile_result be compile_program(program, output_s_path)
    If compile_result is not equal to 0:
        Alert "[runa run] compile: code generation failed"
        Return 1
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: STAGE RUNNERS (assemble / link / execute)
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "run_assemble" takes tmp_s as Integer, tmp_o as Integer, envp as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Mirrors the project's external build recipe "as --64 <x.s> -o <x.o>". The
    command is launched in argv form (never a composed shell string) so paths
    containing spaces or metacharacters cannot be reinterpreted.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Builds the argument List ["as", "--64", tmp_s, "-o", tmp_o], marshals it to a
    NULL-terminated argv (argv[0] = "as"), and invokes process_run on the absolute
    assembler path. Frees the List and the marshalled argv. Returns process_run's
    exit code (0 = success); reports on the nonzero path. Returns 1 if argv
    marshalling failed (allocation).
    @End Implementation
    Let args be proc list_create from ListPrimitive
    proc list_append from ListPrimitive with args, "as"
    proc list_append from ListPrimitive with args, "--64"
    proc list_append from ListPrimitive with args, tmp_s
    proc list_append from ListPrimitive with args, "-o"
    proc list_append from ListPrimitive with args, tmp_o
    Let argv be marshal_argv(args)
    proc list_destroy from ListPrimitive with args
    If argv is equal to 0:
        Alert "[runa run] assemble: could not marshal argv"
        Return 1
    End If
    Let code be proc process_run from ProcessManager with assembler_path(), argv, envp
    free_argv(argv)
    If code is not equal to 0:
        Alert "[runa run] assembly failed"
    End If
    Return code
End Process

Process called "run_link" takes tmp_o as Integer, tmp_exe as Integer, envp as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Mirrors the project's external link recipe "gcc <x.o> <runtime.o> -o <x> -lm".
    gcc is the link driver so crt0/libc startup is supplied. argv form is used so
    the runtime-object and output paths are passed literally.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Builds ["gcc", tmp_o, runtime_object_path(), "-o", tmp_exe, "-lm"], marshals
    to argv (argv[0] = "gcc"), and runs process_run on the absolute gcc path.
    Frees the List and argv. Returns process_run's exit code; reports on nonzero.
    Returns 1 if marshalling failed.
    @End Implementation
    Let args be proc list_create from ListPrimitive
    proc list_append from ListPrimitive with args, "gcc"
    proc list_append from ListPrimitive with args, tmp_o
    proc list_append from ListPrimitive with args, runtime_object_path()
    proc list_append from ListPrimitive with args, "-o"
    proc list_append from ListPrimitive with args, tmp_exe
    proc list_append from ListPrimitive with args, "-lm"
    Let argv be marshal_argv(args)
    proc list_destroy from ListPrimitive with args
    If argv is equal to 0:
        Alert "[runa run] link: could not marshal argv"
        Return 1
    End If
    Let code be proc process_run from ProcessManager with linker_path(), argv, envp
    free_argv(argv)
    If code is not equal to 0:
        Alert "[runa run] link failed"
    End If
    Return code
End Process

Process called "run_execute" takes tmp_exe as Integer, program_args as Integer, envp as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Launches the freshly built program and returns its exit code verbatim so the
    caller can mirror a shell's $? convention. The program's own argument vector
    must begin with argv[0] = the executable path, followed by any caller-supplied
    program arguments, so the running program sees a conventional argv.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Builds an argument List starting with tmp_exe (argv[0]) and then appends each
    element of the caller-supplied program_args List (which may be 0/empty). The
    List is marshalled to a NULL-terminated argv and run with process_run on the
    absolute executable path. Frees the List and argv. Returns the program's exit
    code; returns 1 if marshalling failed.
    @End Implementation
    Let args be proc list_create from ListPrimitive
    proc list_append from ListPrimitive with args, tmp_exe
    If program_args is not equal to 0:
        Let extra_count be proc list_length from ListPrimitive with program_args
        Let extra_index be 0
        While extra_index is less than extra_count:
            Let extra_arg be proc list_get from ListPrimitive with program_args, extra_index
            proc list_append from ListPrimitive with args, extra_arg
            Set extra_index to extra_index plus 1
        End While
    End If
    Let argv be marshal_argv(args)
    proc list_destroy from ListPrimitive with args
    If argv is equal to 0:
        Alert "[runa run] execute: could not marshal argv"
        Return 1
    End If
    Let code be proc process_run from ProcessManager with tmp_exe, argv, envp
    free_argv(argv)
    Return code
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: END-TO-END ORCHESTRATION
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "runa_run" takes input_path as Integer, program_args as Integer, program_envp as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    This is the single public entry point for "runa run": given a source file
    path, it compiles, assembles, links, and executes the program, returning the
    program's exit code (or the failing stage's nonzero code). Each stage is fully
    realized -- the compile reuses the genuine compiler pipeline, and the
    assemble/link/execute stages are real subprocess launches via the Q2a
    primitive. Temp artifacts are derived deterministically from the input
    basename under /tmp and cleaned up best-effort as the pipeline advances, so a
    successful run leaves no residue and a failed run leaves only the artifacts up
    to the failure point (useful for inspection) without ever aborting on a failed
    unlink.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Argument handling:
      - input_path: NUL-terminated absolute path to the .runa source.
      - program_args: a Runa List of NUL-terminated string pointers passed to the
        built program as its arguments (after argv[0]); may be 0 for none.
      - program_envp: a marshalled, NULL-terminated environment vector for the
        BUILD TOOLS and the program. If 0, an empty environment is built via
        empty_envp and freed before return; if nonzero it is borrowed (the caller
        owns it).

    Flow:
      1. Derive basename = basename_of(input_path); build tmp_s/.s, tmp_o/.o,
         tmp_exe (no suffix) via build_temp_path.
      2. Resolve the environment vector (caller's, or a freshly built empty one).
      3. compile_source_to_asm(input_path, tmp_s); nonzero -> clean up and return.
      4. run_assemble(tmp_s, tmp_o); on success the .s is unlinked (no longer
         needed); nonzero -> clean up and return the code.
      5. run_link(tmp_o, tmp_exe); on success the .o is unlinked; nonzero -> clean
         up and return the code.
      6. run_execute(tmp_exe, program_args); capture the exit code.
      7. Final cleanup: unlink any surviving temp artifacts (best-effort), free the
         derived path buffers and the owned empty env (if we built one), and return
         the captured exit code.
    Every allocation made here (paths, owned env) is released on every return
    path. A path-allocation failure (basename/temp path returning 0) is reported
    and returns 1 after releasing whatever was allocated.
    @End Implementation
    Let basename be basename_of(input_path)
    If basename is equal to 0:
        Alert "[runa run] could not derive input basename"
        Return 1
    End If
    Let tmp_s be build_temp_path(basename, ".s")
    Let tmp_o be build_temp_path(basename, ".o")
    Let tmp_exe be build_temp_path(basename, ".out")
    deallocate(basename)
    If tmp_s is equal to 0:
        Alert "[runa run] could not build temp .s path"
        best_effort_unlink(tmp_o)
        best_effort_unlink(tmp_exe)
        Return 1
    End If
    If tmp_o is equal to 0:
        Alert "[runa run] could not build temp .o path"
        deallocate(tmp_s)
        best_effort_unlink(tmp_exe)
        Return 1
    End If
    If tmp_exe is equal to 0:
        Alert "[runa run] could not build temp executable path"
        deallocate(tmp_s)
        deallocate(tmp_o)
        Return 1
    End If

    Note: Resolve the environment vector: borrow the caller's, or own an empty one.
    Let envp be program_envp
    Let owns_envp be 0
    If envp is equal to 0:
        Set envp to empty_envp()
        Set owns_envp to 1
        If envp is equal to 0:
            Alert "[runa run] could not allocate environment vector"
            deallocate(tmp_s)
            deallocate(tmp_o)
            deallocate(tmp_exe)
            Return 1
        End If
    End If

    Note: Stage 1: compile source -> assembly.
    Let compile_code be compile_source_to_asm(input_path, tmp_s)
    If compile_code is not equal to 0:
        best_effort_unlink(tmp_s)
        If owns_envp is equal to 1:
            free_envp(envp)
        End If
        deallocate(tmp_s)
        deallocate(tmp_o)
        deallocate(tmp_exe)
        Return compile_code
    End If

    Note: Stage 2: assemble .s -> .o.
    Let assemble_code be run_assemble(tmp_s, tmp_o, envp)
    best_effort_unlink(tmp_s)
    If assemble_code is not equal to 0:
        best_effort_unlink(tmp_o)
        If owns_envp is equal to 1:
            free_envp(envp)
        End If
        deallocate(tmp_s)
        deallocate(tmp_o)
        deallocate(tmp_exe)
        Return assemble_code
    End If

    Note: Stage 3: link .o + runtime -> executable.
    Let link_code be run_link(tmp_o, tmp_exe, envp)
    best_effort_unlink(tmp_o)
    If link_code is not equal to 0:
        best_effort_unlink(tmp_exe)
        If owns_envp is equal to 1:
            free_envp(envp)
        End If
        deallocate(tmp_s)
        deallocate(tmp_o)
        deallocate(tmp_exe)
        Return link_code
    End If

    Note: Stage 4: execute the program and capture its exit code.
    Let exit_code be run_execute(tmp_exe, program_args, envp)

    Note: Final cleanup (best-effort) and resource release.
    best_effort_unlink(tmp_exe)
    If owns_envp is equal to 1:
        free_envp(envp)
    End If
    deallocate(tmp_s)
    deallocate(tmp_o)
    deallocate(tmp_exe)
    Return exit_code
End Process
